
<div style="line-height: 1.5em; background-color: white; color: black; direction: ltr;" data-mce-style="line-height: 1.5em; background-color: white; color: black; direction: ltr; transition: margin-left 250ms, padding 250ms; -webkit-transition: margin-left 250ms, padding 250ms;"><div style="margin: 0px; position: relative; text-align: center; font-size: 0.8em;" data-mce-style="position: relative; text-align: center; margin: 0px; font-size: 0.8em;"><div><br></div></div><h1 style="border-bottom: 1px solid rgb(170, 170, 170); margin: 0px 0px 0.1em; overflow: hidden; color: black; background-image: none; font-weight: normal; padding-top: 0px; padding-bottom: 0px; font-size: 1.6em; line-height: 1.2em;" data-mce-style="color: black; background-image: none; font-weight: normal; margin: 0px; overflow: hidden; padding-top: 0px; padding-bottom: 0px; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: solid; border-bottom-color: #aaaaaa; font-size: 1.6em; margin-bottom: 0.1em; line-height: 1.2em; margin-top: 0px;" lang="en"><span dir="auto">Hisory of Mobile Learning</span></h1><div style="position: relative; width: 100%; line-height: 1.5em; font-size: 0.8em;" data-mce-style="position: relative; width: 100%; line-height: 1.5em; font-size: 0.8em;"><div style="display: inline; font-size: 92%;" data-mce-style="display: inline; font-size: 92%;">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</div><div style="margin: 0px 0px 1.4em 1em; font-size: 84%; line-height: 1.2em; color: rgb(125, 125, 125); width: auto;" data-mce-style="font-size: 84%; line-height: 1.2em; margin: 0px 0px 1.4em 1em; color: #7d7d7d; width: auto;"><br></div><div style="overflow: hidden; height: 0px; margin-top: -1.4em; margin-bottom: 1.4em;" data-mce-style="overflow: hidden; height: 0px; zoom: 1; margin-top: -1.4em; margin-bottom: 1.4em;">Jump to:<a style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none;" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M-learning#mw-navigation" data-mce-href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M-learning#mw-navigation" data-mce-style="text-decoration: none; color: #0645ad; background-image: none;">navigation</a>, <a style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none;" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M-learning#p-search" data-mce-href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M-learning#p-search" data-mce-style="text-decoration: none; color: #0645ad; background-image: none;">search</a><br data-mce-bogus="1"></div><div style="direction: ltr;" dir="ltr" data-mce-style="direction: ltr;" lang="en"><p style="margin: 0.4em 0px 0.5em; line-height: 1.5em;" data-mce-style="margin: 0.4em 0px 0.5em; line-height: 1.5em;">The term <strong>m-learning</strong> or "mobile learning", has different meanings for different communities, that refer to a subset of <a style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none;" title="Electronic learning" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electronic_learning" data-mce-href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electronic_learning" data-mce-style="text-decoration: none; color: #0645ad; background-image: none;">e-learning</a>, <a style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none;" title="Educational technology" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Educational_technology" data-mce-href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Educational_technology" data-mce-style="text-decoration: none; color: #0645ad; background-image: none;">educational technology</a> and <a style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none;" title="Distance education" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Distance_education" data-mce-href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Distance_education" data-mce-style="text-decoration: none; color: #0645ad; background-image: none;">distance education</a>, that focuses on learning across contexts and learning with <a style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none;" title="Mobile devices" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mobile_devices" data-mce-href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mobile_devices" data-mce-style="text-decoration: none; color: #0645ad; background-image: none;">mobile devices</a>. One definition of mobile learning is, "any sort of learning that happens when the learner is not at a fixed, predetermined location, or learning that happens when the learner takes advantage of the learning opportunities offered by mobile technologies."<sup style="line-height: 1em; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal;" data-mce-style="line-height: 1em; unicode-bidi: -webkit-isolate; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal;"><a style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; white-space: nowrap;" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M-learning#cite_note-1" data-mce-href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M-learning#cite_note-1" data-mce-style="text-decoration: none; color: #0645ad; background-image: none; white-space: nowrap;"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> In other words, with the use of mobile devices, learners can learn anywhere and at any time.<sup style="line-height: 1em; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal;" data-mce-style="line-height: 1em; unicode-bidi: -webkit-isolate; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal;"><a style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; white-space: nowrap;" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M-learning#cite_note-Crescente_2011_111.E2.80.93123-2" data-mce-href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M-learning#cite_note-Crescente_2011_111.E2.80.93123-2" data-mce-style="text-decoration: none; color: #0645ad; background-image: none; white-space: nowrap;"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup><br data-mce-bogus="1"></p><p style="margin: 0.4em 0px 0.5em; line-height: 1.5em;" data-mce-style="margin: 0.4em 0px 0.5em; line-height: 1.5em;">M-learning technologies include handheld computers, <a style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none;" title="MP3 player" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MP3_player" data-mce-href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MP3_player" data-mce-style="text-decoration: none; color: #0645ad; background-image: none;">MP3 players</a>, notebooks, mobile phones and tablets. M-learning focuses on the mobility of the learner, interacting with portable technologies, and learning that reflects a focus on how society and its institutions can accommodate and support an increasingly mobile population. There is also a new direction in m-learning that gives the instructor more mobility and includes creation of on the spot and in the field learning material that predominately uses <a style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none;" title="Smartphone" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Smartphone" data-mce-href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Smartphone" data-mce-style="text-decoration: none; color: #0645ad; background-image: none;">smartphone</a> with special software such as AHG Cloud Note. Using mobile tools for creating learning aides and materials becomes an important part of <a style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none;" title="Informal learning" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Informal_learning" data-mce-href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Informal_learning" data-mce-style="text-decoration: none; color: #0645ad; background-image: none;">informal learning</a>.</p><p style="margin: 0.4em 0px 0.5em; line-height: 1.5em;" data-mce-style="margin: 0.4em 0px 0.5em; line-height: 1.5em;">M-learning is convenient in that it is accessible from virtually anywhere. M-learning, like other forms of <a style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none;" title="E-learning" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E-learning" data-mce-href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E-learning" data-mce-style="text-decoration: none; color: #0645ad; background-image: none;">e-learning</a>, is also collaborative. Sharing is almost instantaneous among everyone using the same content, which leads to the reception of instant feedback and tips. This highly active process has proven to increase exam scores from the fiftieth to the seventieth percentile, and cut the dropout rate in technical fields by 22 percent.<sup style="line-height: 1em; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal;" data-mce-style="line-height: 1em; unicode-bidi: -webkit-isolate; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal;"><a style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; white-space: nowrap;" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M-learning#cite_note-3" data-mce-href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M-learning#cite_note-3" data-mce-style="text-decoration: none; color: #0645ad; background-image: none; white-space: nowrap;"><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup> M-learning also brings strong portability by replacing <a style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none;" title="Book" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book" data-mce-href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book" data-mce-style="text-decoration: none; color: #0645ad; background-image: none;">books</a> and notes with small <a style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none;" title="RAM" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RAM" data-mce-href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RAM" data-mce-style="text-decoration: none; color: #0645ad; background-image: none;">RAMs</a>, filled with tailored learning contents. In addition, it is simple to utilize mobile learning for a more effective and entertaining experience.</p><h3 style="border-bottom: 1px none rgb(170, 170, 170); margin: 0px 0px 0.3em; overflow: hidden; color: black; background-image: none; font-weight: bold; padding-top: 0.5em; padding-bottom: 0.17em; font-size: 132%;" data-mce-style="color: black; background-image: none; font-weight: bold; margin: 0px; overflow: hidden; padding-top: 0.5em; padding-bottom: 0.17em; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: none; border-bottom-color: #aaaaaa; font-size: 132%; margin-bottom: 0.3em;"><span>Pre-1970s</span><span style="font-size: small; font-weight: normal; margin-left: 1em; vertical-align: baseline; line-height: 1em; white-space: nowrap; padding-right: 0.25em;" data-mce-style="-webkit-user-select: none; font-size: small; font-weight: normal; margin-left: 1em; vertical-align: baseline; line-height: 1em; display: inline-block; white-space: nowrap; padding-right: 0.25em; unicode-bidi: -webkit-isolate;"><span></span><span></span></span></h3><p style="margin: 0.4em 0px 0.5em; line-height: 1.5em;" data-mce-style="margin: 0.4em 0px 0.5em; line-height: 1.5em;">Arguably the first instance of mobile learning goes back as far as 1901 when <a style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none;" title="Linguaphone (company)" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linguaphone_%28company%29" data-mce-href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linguaphone_(company)" data-mce-style="text-decoration: none; color: #0645ad; background-image: none;">Linguaphone</a> released a series of language lessons on <a style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none;" title="Wax cylinders" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wax_cylinders" data-mce-href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wax_cylinders" data-mce-style="text-decoration: none; color: #0645ad; background-image: none;">wax cylinders</a>. This was followed up in later years as technology improved, to cover compact <a style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none;" title="Cassette tapes" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cassette_tapes" data-mce-href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cassette_tapes" data-mce-style="text-decoration: none; color: #0645ad; background-image: none;">cassette tapes</a>, <a style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none;" title="8-track tape" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/8-track_tape" data-mce-href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/8-track_tape" data-mce-style="text-decoration: none; color: #0645ad; background-image: none;">8 track tape</a>, and <a style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none;" title="CDs" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CDs" data-mce-href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CDs" data-mce-style="text-decoration: none; color: #0645ad; background-image: none;">CDs</a><sup style="line-height: 1em; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal;" data-mce-style="line-height: 1em; unicode-bidi: -webkit-isolate; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal;"><a style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; white-space: nowrap;" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M-learning#cite_note-linguaphone-4" data-mce-href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M-learning#cite_note-linguaphone-4" data-mce-style="text-decoration: none; color: #0645ad; background-image: none; white-space: nowrap;"><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup><sup style="line-height: 1em; white-space: nowrap;" data-mce-style="line-height: 1em; white-space: nowrap;">[<em><a style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none;" title="Wikipedia:Disputed statement" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Disputed_statement" data-mce-href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Disputed_statement" data-mce-style="text-decoration: none; color: #0645ad; background-image: none;"><span title="The material near this tag is possibly inaccurate or nonfactual. (February 2010)">dubious</span></a> <span>â¬ <a style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none;" title="Talk:M-learning" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Talk:M-learning#Dubious" data-mce-href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Talk:M-learning#Dubious" data-mce-style="text-decoration: none; color: #0645ad; background-image: none;">discuss</a></span></em>]</sup></p><h3 style="border-bottom: 1px none rgb(170, 170, 170); margin: 0px 0px 0.3em; overflow: hidden; color: black; background-image: none; font-weight: bold; padding-top: 0.5em; padding-bottom: 0.17em; font-size: 132%;" data-mce-style="color: black; background-image: none; font-weight: bold; margin: 0px; overflow: hidden; padding-top: 0.5em; padding-bottom: 0.17em; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: none; border-bottom-color: #aaaaaa; font-size: 132%; margin-bottom: 0.3em;"><span>1970s, 1980s</span><span style="font-size: small; font-weight: normal; margin-left: 1em; vertical-align: baseline; line-height: 1em; white-space: nowrap; padding-right: 0.25em;" data-mce-style="-webkit-user-select: none; font-size: small; font-weight: normal; margin-left: 1em; vertical-align: baseline; line-height: 1em; display: inline-block; white-space: nowrap; padding-right: 0.25em; unicode-bidi: -webkit-isolate;"><span></span><span></span></span></h3><p style="margin: 0.4em 0px 0.5em; line-height: 1.5em;" data-mce-style="margin: 0.4em 0px 0.5em; line-height: 1.5em;">In 1968 <a style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none;" title="Alan Kay" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alan_Kay" data-mce-href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alan_Kay" data-mce-style="text-decoration: none; color: #0645ad; background-image: none;">Alan Kay</a> and his colleagues in the Learning Research Group at Xerox Palo Alto Research Center [PARC] propose the <a style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none;" title="Dynabook" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dynabook" data-mce-href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dynabook" data-mce-style="text-decoration: none; color: #0645ad; background-image: none;">Dynabook</a> as a book-sized computer to run dynamic simulations for learning. "The Dynabook would carry an encyclopedia of information inside its circuits and plug into readily available networks containing the sum of human knowledge. Anybody from grade school up would be able to program it to do whatever was wanted. And there's no reason it would even have to be a book; it could just as well be a wristwatch, or woven into a T-shirt."<sup style="line-height: 1em; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal;" data-mce-style="line-height: 1em; unicode-bidi: -webkit-isolate; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal;"><a style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; white-space: nowrap;" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M-learning#cite_note-5" data-mce-href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M-learning#cite_note-5" data-mce-style="text-decoration: none; color: #0645ad; background-image: none; white-space: nowrap;"><span>[</span>5<span>]</span></a></sup><br data-mce-bogus="1"></p><h3 style="border-bottom: 1px none rgb(170, 170, 170); margin: 0px 0px 0.3em; overflow: hidden; color: black; background-image: none; font-weight: bold; padding-top: 0.5em; padding-bottom: 0.17em; font-size: 132%;" data-mce-style="color: black; background-image: none; font-weight: bold; margin: 0px; overflow: hidden; padding-top: 0.5em; padding-bottom: 0.17em; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: none; border-bottom-color: #aaaaaa; font-size: 132%; margin-bottom: 0.3em;"><span>1990s</span><span style="font-size: small; font-weight: normal; margin-left: 1em; vertical-align: baseline; line-height: 1em; white-space: nowrap; padding-right: 0.25em;" data-mce-style="-webkit-user-select: none; font-size: small; font-weight: normal; margin-left: 1em; vertical-align: baseline; line-height: 1em; display: inline-block; white-space: nowrap; padding-right: 0.25em; unicode-bidi: -webkit-isolate;"><span></span><span></span></span></h3><p style="margin: 0.4em 0px 0.5em; line-height: 1.5em;" data-mce-style="margin: 0.4em 0px 0.5em; line-height: 1.5em;">In May 1991, Apple Classrooms of Tomorrow (ACOT) in partnership with Orange Grove Middle School of Tucson, Arizona, used mobile computers connected by wireless networks for the 'Wireless Coyote' project.<sup style="line-height: 1em; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal;" data-mce-style="line-height: 1em; unicode-bidi: -webkit-isolate; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal;"><a style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none; white-space: nowrap;" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M-learning#cite_note-.28Grant.2C_2003.29-6" data-mce-href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M-learning#cite_note-.28Grant.2C_2003.29-6" data-mce-style="text-decoration: none; color: #0645ad; background-image: none; white-space: nowrap;"><span>[</span>6<span>]</span></a></sup> Universities in Europe and Asia developed and evaluated mobile learning for students. Palm corporation offered grants to universities and companies who created and tested the use of Mobile Learning on the PalmOS platform. Knowledgility created the first mobile learning modules for CCNA, A+ and MCSE certification using the core tools that later became <strong>LMA.</strong></p><h3 style="border-bottom: 1px none rgb(170, 170, 170); margin: 0px 0px 0.3em; overflow: hidden; color: black; background-image: none; font-weight: bold; padding-top: 0.5em; padding-bottom: 0.17em; font-size: 132%;" data-mce-style="color: black; background-image: none; font-weight: bold; margin: 0px; overflow: hidden; padding-top: 0.5em; padding-bottom: 0.17em; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: none; border-bottom-color: #aaaaaa; font-size: 132%; margin-bottom: 0.3em;"><span>2000s</span><span style="font-size: small; font-weight: normal; margin-left: 1em; vertical-align: baseline; line-height: 1em; white-space: nowrap; padding-right: 0.25em;" data-mce-style="-webkit-user-select: none; font-size: small; font-weight: normal; margin-left: 1em; vertical-align: baseline; line-height: 1em; display: inline-block; white-space: nowrap; padding-right: 0.25em; unicode-bidi: -webkit-isolate;"><span></span><span></span></span></h3><p style="margin: 0.4em 0px 0.5em; line-height: 1.5em;" data-mce-style="margin: 0.4em 0px 0.5em; line-height: 1.5em;">The European Commission began to fund the major multi-national MOBIlearn and <a style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(51, 102, 187); background-image: url(data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAAoAAAAKCAYAAACNMs+9AAAAVElEQVR42n3PgQkAIAhEUXdqJ3dqJ3e6IoTPUSQcgj4EQ5IlUiLE0Jil3PECXhcHGBhZ8kg4hwxAu3MZeCGeyFnAXp4hqNQPnt7QL0nADpD6wHccLvnAKksq8iiaAAAAAElFTkSuQmCC); padding-right: 13px; background-position: 100% 50%;" href="http://www.m-learning.org/archive" rel="nofollow" target="_blank" data-mce-href="http://www.m-learning.org/archive" data-mce-style="text-decoration: none; color: #3366bb; background-image: url(data:image/png; base64,ivborw0kggoaaaansuheugaaaaoaaaakcayaaacnms+9aaaaveleqvr42n3pgqkaiaheuxdqj3dqj3e6iotpusqcgj4eq5iluile0jil3pecxhchgbhz8kg4hwxau3mzecgeyfnaxp4hqnqpnt7ql0nadpd6whcclvnakksq8iiaaaaaaelftksuqmcc);padding-right: 13px; background-position: 100% 50%; background-repeat: no-repeat no-repeat;">M-learning</a> projects.</p><p style="margin: 0.4em 0px 0.5em; line-height: 1.5em;" data-mce-style="margin: 0.4em 0px 0.5em; line-height: 1.5em;">Companies, specializing in these three core areas of mobile learning were formed.</p><ol style="margin: 0.3em 0px 0px 3.2em; padding: 0px; line-height: 1.5em; list-style-image: none;" data-mce-style="line-height: 1.5em; margin: 0.3em 0px 0px 3.2em; padding: 0px; list-style-image: none;"><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;" data-mce-style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">Authoring and Publishing</li><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;" data-mce-style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">Delivery and Tracking</li><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;" data-mce-style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">Content Development</li></ol><p style="margin: 0.4em 0px 0.5em; line-height: 1.5em;" data-mce-style="margin: 0.4em 0px 0.5em; line-height: 1.5em;">Conferences and trade shows were created to specifically deal with mobile learning and handheld education, including: <a style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none;" title="MLearn" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MLearn" data-mce-href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MLearn" data-mce-style="text-decoration: none; color: #0645ad; background-image: none;">mLearn</a>, WMUTE, and <a style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none;" title="IADIS Mobile Learning" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IADIS_Mobile_Learning" data-mce-href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IADIS_Mobile_Learning" data-mce-style="text-decoration: none; color: #0645ad; background-image: none;">IADIS Mobile Learning</a> international conference series, ICML in Jordan, Mobile Learning in Malaysia, Handheld Learning in London, and SALT Mobile in USA. In 2003, "Hello China" pioneered the use of mobile phones for large scale training by sending words to learn to the mobile phones of participants throughout China.</p><h3 style="border-bottom: 1px none rgb(170, 170, 170); margin: 0px 0px 0.3em; overflow: hidden; color: black; background-image: none; font-weight: bold; padding-top: 0.5em; padding-bottom: 0.17em; font-size: 132%;" data-mce-style="color: black; background-image: none; font-weight: bold; margin: 0px; overflow: hidden; padding-top: 0.5em; padding-bottom: 0.17em; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: none; border-bottom-color: #aaaaaa; font-size: 132%; margin-bottom: 0.3em;"><span>2010 and beyond</span><span style="font-size: small; font-weight: normal; margin-left: 1em; vertical-align: baseline; line-height: 1em; white-space: nowrap; padding-right: 0.25em;" data-mce-style="-webkit-user-select: none; font-size: small; font-weight: normal; margin-left: 1em; vertical-align: baseline; line-height: 1em; display: inline-block; white-space: nowrap; padding-right: 0.25em; unicode-bidi: -webkit-isolate;"><span></span><span></span></span></h3><p style="margin: 0.4em 0px 0.5em; line-height: 1.5em;" data-mce-style="margin: 0.4em 0px 0.5em; line-height: 1.5em;">As a large number of smart mobile devices came onto the market, m-learning developers faced a decision as to which devices (smartphone or tablet) and operating systems they would target.</p><p style="margin: 0.4em 0px 0.5em; line-height: 1.5em;" data-mce-style="margin: 0.4em 0px 0.5em; line-height: 1.5em;">Apple, Android and Blackberry were, for several years during this decade, the three most popular operating systems. Blackberry OS is enduring a diminishing prominence. Clearly, the Apple iOS and Android operating systems are premier and attract the most activity among both developers and users. Multi-device learning design is becoming increasingly important as learning designers set out to design once and deliver to all three operating systems as well as a variety of device sizes.</p><p style="margin: 0.4em 0px 0.5em; line-height: 1.5em;" data-mce-style="margin: 0.4em 0px 0.5em; line-height: 1.5em;">2011 and 2012 saw the increasing availability of multi-device authoring tools such as Captivate, Articulate Storyline, Lectora and GoMoLearning. These tools allow e-learning courses to be delivered to a variety of mobile operating systems and devices as well as to PCs, although not all tools output to all operating systems and devices.</p><h2 style="border-bottom: 1px solid rgb(170, 170, 170); margin: 0px 0px 0.6em; overflow: hidden; color: black; background-image: none; font-weight: normal; padding-top: 0.5em; padding-bottom: 0.17em; font-size: 150%;" data-mce-style="color: black; background-image: none; font-weight: normal; margin: 0px; overflow: hidden; padding-top: 0.5em; padding-bottom: 0.17em; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: solid; border-bottom-color: #aaaaaa; font-size: 150%; margin-bottom: 0.6em;"><span>References</span><span style="font-size: small; font-weight: normal; margin-left: 1em; vertical-align: baseline; line-height: 1em; white-space: nowrap; padding-right: 0.25em;" data-mce-style="-webkit-user-select: none; font-size: small; font-weight: normal; margin-left: 1em; vertical-align: baseline; line-height: 1em; display: inline-block; white-space: nowrap; padding-right: 0.25em; unicode-bidi: -webkit-isolate;"><span></span><span></span></span></h2><div style="font-size: 90%; margin-bottom: 0.5em; list-style-type: decimal;" data-mce-style="font-size: 90%; margin-bottom: 0.5em; list-style-type: decimal;"><ol style="margin: 0.3em 0px 0.5em 3.2em; padding: 0px; line-height: 1.5em; list-style-image: none; font-size: 100%; list-style-type: inherit;" data-mce-style="line-height: 1.5em; margin: 0.3em 0px 0px 3.2em; padding: 0px; list-style-image: none; font-size: 100%; margin-bottom: 0.5em; list-style-type: inherit;"><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;" data-mce-style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;"><span><strong><a style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(6, 69, 173); background-image: none;" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M-learning#cite_ref-1" data-mce-href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M-learning#cite_ref-1" data-mce-style="text-decoration: none; color: #0645ad; background-image: none;"><span style="border: 0px none ; padding: 0px; overflow: hidden; top: -99999px; clip: rect(1px, 1px, 1px, 1px); position: absolute; height: 1px; width: 1px;" data-mce-style="top: -99999px; clip: rect(1px 1px 1px 1px); overflow: hidden; position: absolute; padding: 0px; border: 0px; height: 1px; width: 1px;">Jump up </span>^</a></strong></span> <span><span style="" data-mce-style="word-wrap: break-word;"><a style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(51, 102, 187); background-image: url(https://bits.wikimedia.org//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/23/Icons-mini-file_acrobat.gif); padding-right: 18px; background-position: 100% 50%;" href="http://www.mobilearn.org/download/results/guidelines.pdf" rel="nofollow" target="_blank" data-mce-href="http://www.mobilearn.org/download/results/guidelines.pdf" data-mce-style="text-decoration: none; color: #3366bb; background-image: url('https://bits.wikimedia.org//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/23/Icons-mini-file_acrobat.gif'); padding-right: 18px; background-position: 100% 50%; background-repea